<TITLE> Babar shown arrested for Aug 21 blasts </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 26 (bdnews24.com)  BNP's former state minister for home Lutfuzzaman Babar, already behind bars, was shown arrested Monday for the Aug 21 2004 grenade attack on an Awami league rally. Investigation officer, CID's Abdul Kahhar Akand, told bdnews24.com they had sought 10 days remand for the former state minister from the Dhaka Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court. Babar began serving 17 years on March 5 this year having been convicted in an arms case. The 2004 grenade attack on an AL rally on Bangabandhu Avenue killed at least 23 people and left scores injured, including the then opposition leader Sheikh Hasina, now prime minister. Some 22 people stand charged in the cases, including BNP leader Nasiruddin Ahmed Pintu, his brother, also the alleged grenade supplier, Maolana Tajuddin, and Mufti Hannan, leader of banned Islamist outfit Harkatul Jihad. Of them, 13 accused including Pintu and Hannan are now behind bars while the remaining accused are on the run. The Criminal Investigation Department pressed charges in two cases, a murder case and an explosives case, on June 11 last year. Some 61 among 412 witnesses have so far testified. The witnesses include president Zillur Rahman, prime minister Sheikh Hasina, home minister Sahara Khatun and AL's former general secretary Abdul Jalil. bdnew
